{"parentUuid":"a11fd117-0a91-4144-98df-6aa63f685094","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/jwilger/projects/todo_list","sessionId":"2e8aac70-7083-46be-b97a-0325443201fe","version":"2.1.39","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a3d7295","slug":"happy-baking-hartmanis","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":"<teammate-message teammate_id=\"heydon-pickering\" color=\"red\" summary=\"A11y feedback on Waiting For design proposal\">\nHeydon here with accessibility feedback on the proposed design.\n\n**Generally sound.** The plan covers the key accessibility bases. A few points:\n\n### Accessible Names on Action Buttons\n\nYou mention `aria-label` including item title, e.g., \"Received: Fix server bug\". That works, but consider that the waiting-for item has TWO identifying fields: title and waiting_on. The accessible name should include both for disambiguation. If I have two items called \"Invoice\" — one waiting on Alice, one waiting on Bob — \"Received: Invoice\" is ambiguous.\n\n**Suggestion**: Use pattern like \"Received: Invoice — waiting on Alice\" or include the waiting_on in the button's accessible name. Similarly for Delete and Edit buttons.\n\nAlternatively, use `aria-labelledby` pointing to the item's title AND waiting_on elements rather than duplicating text in `aria-label`. This keeps the accessible name in sync with the visible text automatically.\n\n### \"Received\" as Complete Action Label\n\nFrom an accessibility standpoint, \"Received\" is fine as a verb-action label. It describes what happened. My only concern: will screen reader users understand that \"Received\" means \"mark this item as done\"? It's GTD-specific vocabulary. Consider whether `title` attribute or additional context helps, but don't over-engineer it — the surrounding list context (\"Waiting For\" page heading) should make it clear enough.\n\n### Form Structure\n\nTwo fields (title + waiting_on) — good that both have visible `<label>` elements. A `<fieldset>` with `<legend>` would be appropriate if these fields form a logical group (\"Add a Waiting For item\" or similar). Don't nest fieldsets.\n\n### Date Display\n\nYou mention showing \"date added\" — please use `<time datetime=\"...\">` element with ISO 8601 datetime attribute. The visible text can be a human-friendly format, but the machine-readable datetime helps assistive technology and is semantic HTML.\n\n### Empty State\n\n\"Nothing to follow up on. Items you're waiting on from others will appear here.\" — Good. Clear, helpful, not patronizing.\n\n### `role=\"list\"` on `<ul>`\n\nYou mentioned `<ul>` with `role=\"list\"`. This is only needed if CSS `list-style: none` strips the list semantics in Safari/VoiceOver (which it does). If you're using `list-style: none`, then yes, add `role=\"list\"`. Otherwise the native `<ul>` semantics are sufficient. Check what the existing patterns do — consistency matters.\n\n### Focus Management\n\nGlad to see focus management JS mentioned from day one. After deletion, focus should move to the next item in the list (or the previous if it was the last item, or the add form if the list is now empty). After completing/receiving, same pattern. After inline edit cancel, focus returns to the edit trigger button.\n\n### One Minor Note\n\nFor the inline edit form: make sure the cancel action is a `<button>`, not a link. Cancelling an edit is an action, not navigation.\n\n**No blocking concerns at this stage.** The design is solid. I'll do full scrutiny once code is written.\n\n+1 on deferring convert-to-next-action to a follow-up — simpler first commit means fewer accessibility patterns to get wrong.\n</teammate-message>"},"uuid":"5f503716-9ae1-4a7d-9b4b-7f54fc68a9ea","timestamp":"2026-02-13T00:15:30.258Z"}
