{"parentUuid":"03e6b077-0a3b-4160-8a4d-fce19d161e58","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/jwilger/projects/todo_list","sessionId":"2e8aac70-7083-46be-b97a-0325443201fe","version":"2.1.39","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a3d7295","slug":"happy-baking-hartmanis","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01KzBwWepH1jrPRL5iJNgaTY","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01HuzVFEd7dnQLG9hk51ThiR","name":"SendMessage","input":{"type":"message","recipient":"heydon-pickering","content":"Heydon, the implementation is complete. Let me address each of your points:\n\n**Accessible names on action buttons** -- Currently using `aria-label=\"Received: {{ item.title }}\"`, `aria-label=\"Delete: {{ item.title }}\"`, `aria-label=\"Edit: {{ item.title }}\"`. Your point about disambiguation with waiting_on is valid -- two items called \"Invoice\" would be ambiguous. I can update these to include the person, e.g., `aria-label=\"Received: Invoice (waiting on Alice)\"`. Do you consider this blocking? I can fix it now.\n\n**\"Received\" as complete label** -- Agreed the surrounding context (\"Waiting For\" page heading) makes it clear. Keeping as-is.\n\n**Form structure / fieldset** -- The add form does NOT use a `<fieldset>` with `<legend>`. The two fields have individual `<label>` elements (\"What are you waiting for?\" and \"Who or what?\") but no grouping fieldset. The existing patterns (Next Actions, Projects, Inbox) also don't use fieldset for their add forms. Should I add one here, or keep it consistent with the existing pattern?\n\n**`<time>` element** -- NOT currently used. Carson also flagged this. The date is a bare `<span class=\"waiting-for-item__date\">{{ item.date_added }}</span>`. I can add `<time datetime=\"{{ item.iso_date }}\">{{ item.date_added }}</time>` but it would require adding an ISO date field to the view struct. Do you consider this blocking?\n\n**Empty state** -- Implemented as you described.\n\n**`role=\"list\"` on `<ul>`** -- Yes, using `role=\"list\"` because all our lists use `list-style: none` in CSS. This is consistent with every other list template in the project (inbox, next-actions, projects, contexts, todos, nav). See `templates/waiting_for.html` line 62.\n\n**Focus management** -- Implemented in `static/js/waiting-for-focus.js`. After deletion/completion: focuses next sibling item, falls back to previous sibling, falls back to add form title input. After inline edit cancel: HTMX swap restores the item view (focus handled by the swap). Empty state transition is handled.\n\n**Cancel as `<a>` vs `<button>`** -- The cancel action is currently an `<a>` element (line 34-41 of `templates/waiting_for_edit.html`). I hear your point that Cancel is semantically an action, not navigation. However, the existing patterns for Projects (`templates/project_edit.html`) and Next Actions (`templates/next_action_edit.html`) also use `<a>` for Cancel. The `<a>` does double duty: it's the no-JS fallback (navigates to the item URL to re-fetch the non-edit view) and the HTMX-enhanced version (swaps the item fragment in place). Changing it to `<button>` would break the no-JS fallback. Should I keep it consistent with existing patterns, or do you want me to change all of them?\n\nPlease let me know which items you consider **blocking** so I can fix them before the commit. Key questions:\n1. Add waiting_on person to aria-labels? (I'm inclined to do this)\n2. Add `<time>` element? (requires view struct change)\n3. Add `<fieldset>`/`<legend>` to add form?\n4. Change Cancel from `<a>` to `<button>`?","summary":"Addressing Heydon's a11y feedback, asking which items are blocking"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":529,"cache_read_input_tokens":136699,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":529,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global","research_preview_2026_02"